## AdapterCard Label Display and Binding Status

Update the AdapterCard to show the adapter label, binding status dot, and bound agent names.

### Label Display

In `apps/client/src/layers/features/relay/ui/AdapterCard.tsx`, update the card header to show both the custom label (primary) and the adapter type's displayName (secondary):

```tsx
<div className="flex flex-col">
  <span className="text-sm font-medium">
    {instance.label || instance.status.displayName || instance.id}
  </span>
  {instance.label && (
    <span className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
      {manifest.displayName}
    </span>
  )}
</div>
```

The `instance.label` comes from the `CatalogInstance` type updated in task 1.2.

### Binding Status and Bound Agents

Add new data to the card using `useBindings()` and `useRegisteredAgents()` hooks. Since `AdapterCard` is in `features/relay/ui/`, it can import from entities:

```typescript
import { useBindings } from '@/layers/entities/binding';
import { useRegisteredAgents } from '@/layers/entities/mesh';
```

Derive binding info from the hooks:

```typescript
const { data: allBindings = [] } = useBindings();
const { data: agentsData } = useRegisteredAgents();

const adapterBindings = useMemo(() => {
  return allBindings.filter(b => b.adapterId === instance.id);
}, [allBindings, instance.id]);

const boundAgents = useMemo(() => {
  const agents = agentsData?.agents ?? [];
  return adapterBindings.map(b => {
    const agent = agents.find(a => a.id === b.agentId);
    return { agentId: b.agentId, agentName: agent?.name ?? b.agentId, label: b.label };
  });
}, [adapterBindings, agentsData]);

const hasBindings = adapterBindings.length > 0;
```

